Hearst Castle is a National and California Historical Landmark mansion located on the Central Coast of California, United States. It was designed by architect Julia Morgan between 1919 and 1947 for newspaper magnate William Randolph Hearst, who died in 1951. In 1957, the Hearst Corporation donated the property to the state of California. Since that time it has been maintained as a state historic park where the estate, and its considerable collection of art and antiques, is open for public tours. Despite its location far from any urban center, the site attracts about one million visitors per year. Hearst Castle, San Simeon, CA Jun '07 Neptune pool is 104 feet long, 58 feet wide and 95 feet wide at alcove. It is 3.5 feet deep at the west end, 10 feet at drains and holds 345,000 gallons of water. Other unique aspects of the Neptune Pool include the oil burning heating system, the light-veined Vermont marble decorating the pools and colonnades, and four 17-century Italian bas-reliefs on the sides of the colonnades.

We were told their names are Charm, Bloom, and Joy - we since found out that is not at all accurate. However, there are many different interpretations or representations of the various Greek and Roman myths by various scholars, artist, and poets. *One may say they are the goddesses of charm, beauty, nature, human creativity and fertility. From youngest to oldest: Aglaea ("Splendor"), Euphrosyne ("Mirth"), and Thalia ("Good Cheer"). Or they may be Cleta rather than Thalia, or any of Auxo, Charis, Hegemone, Phaenna, or Pasithea. Or any three out of Antheia, Eudaimonia, Paidia, Pandaisia, Pannychis - all referring to the Charites as patronesses of amusement and festivities. Charisma, Persuasion, Sleep and Grace are also said to be of the Graces. *per my interpretation of the Wikipedia article of the Charities as they relate to the Graces.
